@lslah: This comes straight from the Google version. Your example suggests that this is more of a C++ convention. Consider this function:

```
int f(char_u *buf1, size_t len1, char_u *buf2, size_t len2);
```

Moving the pointers to the end makes no sense. Should we remove this section?

@justinmk:

> But the explanation is short enough to include, plus the "reveal" buttons hide the information, anyways.

I've removed this part mainly because it appeals to VLAs not being standard and C++ and C++ having Vectors etc. I'll add a short note citing stack overflow.

``` C
int mch_dirname(char_u *buf, int len);
int mch_dirname(int len, char_u *buf);
int f(char_u *buf1, size_t len1, char_u *buf2, size_t len2);
```

I come from a C++ background. There the idiomatic approach would be to introduce a new type wrapping `*buf` and `len`. I know string handling has been discussed elsewhere, was a decision reached?

> Here is one important difference between inline functions in C and C++: [...]

Is [this](http://www.greenend.org.uk/rjk/tech/inline.html) an accurate description of `inline` in C? If so the behaviour is generally identical to C++'s `inline` keyword, which compilers will happily ignore.

What about the usual

```
if ((var = func()) == NULL)
    return FAIL;
```

vs

```
var = func();
if (var == NULL)
    return FAIL;
```

. I would prefer the first variant unless resulting line exceeds 80 character limit, in which case the second is better.

@davidzchen:

> Is there a particular reason why we are only allowing postfix i++ and rather than prefix ++i?

i++ is more common in C code. Using ++i over i++ is a C++ convention (see the Google style guide.)

@jszakmeister: How about the following:

---

Prefer

```
if ((x = f()) != A)
```

if x is only used in the block following the if.

Prefer

```
while ((x = f()) != A)
```

over

```
x = f();
while (x != A) {
  ...
  x = f();
}
```

---

The first one seems to be a very powerful hint that helps when reading the code.

> Post an example.

``` c
/// Brief description of the function.
///
/// Detailed description.
/// May span multiple paragraphs.
///
/// @param arg1 Description of arg1
/// @param arg2 Description of arg2. May span
///        multiple lines.
///
/// @return Description of the return value.
Iterator *get_iterator(void *arg1, void *arg2)
{
    ....
}
```

> ```
> :h gq
> ```

``` c
/// Brief description.
///
/// Hello.  Here's a long paragraph describing something and needs to get reflowed onto multiple lines.
///
void foo(void)
{
}
```

Using a visual line selection for the line containing "Hello" and using `gq`, I end up with:

``` c
/// Brief description.
///
/// Hello.  Here's a long paragraph describing something and needs to get
//reflowed onto multiple lines.
///
void foo(void)
{
}
```

...which is not the desired result.  Do you have something setup so that you get better results?

> I don't like what you're trying to imply here. If anything I want to get this out of the way so that I can continue to work on clint.py. @ZyX-I is working on his vim2lua compiler, @lslah is working on removing dead code. Sure, this issue is bikeshedding, but that doesn't mean that it's blocking the rest of the project.

@mahkoh That wasn't an attack.  It was just a call to make sure that we look for actual bugs when reviewing code--I've seen many reviews on other projects dwindle to nit-picking over coding style and there was no other substance to the review.

I don't think it's bike-shedding (well, I guess there's a little of that with anything subjective like a coding standard), and I don't think it's blocking the rest of the project.  But you cut out the important bit:

> All that said, I'm glad you and others are spending time trying to work out the details. In the end, it will make for a much cleaner code base (assuming we stick to it).

Which was a complement to you and the others participating for getting this done. :-)

@Gaelan True, but there was still an option in the vote that used tabs for indentation and spaces for alignment. I was also open to additional options but at that time, nobody proposed smart tabs and the overwhelming support (see results tally) was for the three options that used 2 spaces for indentation.

At this point, I don't have much appetite for dragging on the deliberation for trying to decide on a coding style longer since we have already spent more than a week on it.

I'll leave it up to @tarruda and the project collaborators to decide whether to continue this discussion, have another vote, or just use the convention that we already have.
